\begin_layout Abstract
[Placeholder abstract.
 This paper follows a three-act structure.
 Act 1 (Experiment 1): We deploy a quality measurement and digital monitoring
 system---milk analyzers coupled with digitalized bookkeeping---at dairy
 collection centers in Uganda and show that this quality infrastructure
 improves milk quality practices but does not generate quality-differentiated
 pricing---an enforcement equilibrium rather than a market for quality.
 Act 2 (Model): We develop a simple model with parameter alpha governing
 the strength of the price channel to rationalize these findings.
 Act 3 (Experiment 2): We directly activate the price channel through quality
 bonuses and show that explicit price incentives elicit further quality improvements,
 confirming that the missing ingredient was price differentiation, not information.]
\end_layout

