\begin_layout Section
A Model of Quality Infrastructure and Quality Incentives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:model"

\end_inset

This section presents a simple model to rationalize the findings from Experiment
 1.
 The model shows how a quality measurement and digital monitoring system
 can improve quality through two distinct channels---enforcement and price
 differentiation---and how the relative importance of these channels depends
 on a single parameter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[Placeholder for model setup.
 Consider an MCC that procures milk from farmers.
 The MCC has access to a quality measurement and digital monitoring system
 that reveals milk quality (fat content, adulteration) and tracks quality
 records across deliveries and over time.
 The parameter alpha in [0,1] governs how the MCC uses this information:]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[When alpha = 0, the MCC uses the measurement and monitoring system purely
 for enforcement: milk below a minimum quality threshold is rejected, but
 all accepted milk receives the same price.
 The digital records enable systematic detection of repeat offenders.
 This is an enforcement-only equilibrium.]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[When alpha > 0, the MCC uses the measurement and monitoring system for
 price differentiation: higher-quality milk receives a higher price, with
 digital records providing the basis for quality-based payment schedules.
 The strength of the price channel is increasing in alpha.]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[Placeholder for model predictions.
 The model nests two channels:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 Enforcement channel (alpha = 0): The quality measurement and monitoring
 system reduces adulteration by raising the probability of detection and
 rejection, with digital records enabling systematic tracking of quality
 patterns.
 Quality improves but prices do not differentiate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Price channel (alpha > 0): The system enables quality-differentiated pricing,
 with digital quality records providing the basis for continuous incentives
 for quality improvement beyond the minimum threshold.]
\end_layout

